WEBVTT

00:01.201 --> 00:04.170
[jazz music]

00:04.204 --> 00:11.011
♪ ♪

00:20.453 --> 00:22.422
[applause]

00:22.455 --> 00:24.090
- From
the Penn & Teller Theater

00:24.124 --> 00:26.226
at the Rio Hotel in Las Vegas,

00:26.259 --> 00:30.497
here's our host,
Alyson Hannigan!

00:30.530 --> 00:33.500
[cheers and applause]

00:33.533 --> 00:40.306
♪ ♪

00:42.208 --> 00:44.411
- Welcome to "Fool Us."

00:44.444 --> 00:48.081
I don't think anyone's ever
compared Las Vegas to Camelot,

00:48.114 --> 00:50.917
but every year magicians make
the pilgrimage here

00:50.950 --> 00:54.087
to try and pull off
the holy grail of magic--

00:54.120 --> 00:58.124
to do a trick good enough
to fool true magic royalty--

00:58.158 --> 01:00.960
our very own
King Arthur and Merlin,

01:00.994 --> 01:02.862
Penn and Teller!

01:02.896 --> 01:05.632
[cheers and applause]

01:05.665 --> 01:12.238
♪ ♪

01:19.045 --> 01:21.347
Don't forget--anyone who fools
Penn and Teller

01:21.381 --> 01:23.516
gets the prestigious
"Fool Us" trophy

01:23.550 --> 01:25.085
and a trip back to Vegas

01:25.118 --> 01:27.053
to perform
with Penn and Teller.

01:27.087 --> 01:29.422
Here's our first
potential fooler.

01:31.791 --> 01:34.194
[upbeat music]

01:34.227 --> 01:37.530
- The main reason I do magic
is simply for the reactions.

01:37.564 --> 01:39.599
I have a TV show
called "Tricked."

01:39.632 --> 01:41.234
It's a hidden-camera show
where people don't know

01:41.267 --> 01:42.235
I'm actually a magician.

01:42.268 --> 01:43.503
Chicken salad?
- Yeah.

01:43.536 --> 01:44.771
- So, for example,
I could, like, a clerk

01:44.804 --> 01:46.906
at a sandwich shop,
and somebody would order,

01:46.940 --> 01:49.175
like, a chicken sub
and a live chicken comes out.

01:49.209 --> 01:51.077
- [gasps]
Are you kidding me?

01:51.111 --> 01:52.212
- Just...
[imitates explosion]

01:52.245 --> 01:53.580
- This is the coolest thing

01:53.613 --> 01:56.182
that has ever happened to me
in my entire life.

01:56.216 --> 01:57.784
- I like to melt
people's brains.

01:57.817 --> 02:00.053
A whole brain trust of
magicians actually helped me

02:00.053 --> 02:01.688
create the trick
you're gonna see tonight--

02:01.721 --> 02:03.389
a squad of illusionists

02:03.423 --> 02:05.291
specifically to fool
Penn and Teller.

02:05.325 --> 02:06.192
So watch out.
We're coming for you.

02:06.226 --> 02:07.694
If I do stump them,

02:07.727 --> 02:10.330
I want to do it in a way
that'll make them respect me.

02:10.363 --> 02:11.965
No red herrings,

02:11.998 --> 02:14.167
no weird moves to make
them think something else--

02:14.200 --> 02:16.870
I want to be
an honorable fooler.

02:16.903 --> 02:20.406
[cheers and applause]

02:20.440 --> 02:23.810
- Please welcome the manic
magic of Eric LeClerc.

02:23.843 --> 02:26.045
- [screams]

02:26.079 --> 02:28.248
Yeah!

02:28.281 --> 02:31.584
Whoo!
What's up, everybody?

02:31.618 --> 02:34.220
Whoo!

02:34.254 --> 02:36.623
Look, Mom,
I made it to Vegas!

02:39.893 --> 02:42.762
This is for all the other moms.

02:42.795 --> 02:44.264
And some dads.

02:44.297 --> 02:45.031
You know,
when I heard I was gonna be

02:45.064 --> 02:46.766
on "Penn & Teller: Fool Us,"

02:46.799 --> 02:48.434
I nearly shipped myself,

02:48.468 --> 02:50.103
because it's cheaper
than plane tickets.

02:50.136 --> 02:51.437
And--

02:51.471 --> 02:54.574
No, ship, ship myself,
like, in a box--shipping.

02:54.607 --> 02:56.609
In a box.

02:56.643 --> 02:58.444
I realize that is a dad joke.

02:58.478 --> 03:00.847
I'm allowed one,
even though I don't have kids.

03:00.880 --> 03:03.816
Whoo! Big win!
[applause]

03:03.850 --> 03:05.485
That gets applause?

03:05.518 --> 03:07.287
I'm into it.
I'm into it!

03:07.320 --> 03:09.722
[applause continues]

03:09.756 --> 03:11.391
Hi.

03:11.424 --> 03:12.692
Ladies and gentlemen,
our experiment today

03:12.725 --> 03:14.727
is gonna require
the use of an assistant.

03:14.761 --> 03:15.728
And who do we have here?

03:15.762 --> 03:17.363
- Fabian.
- Fabian, everybody!

03:17.397 --> 03:21.834
[cheers and applause]

03:21.868 --> 03:23.069
Fabian, think of this.

03:23.102 --> 03:25.338
One in 52--

03:25.371 --> 03:27.640
those are the odds
that most magicians use

03:27.674 --> 03:29.409
to prove their magical powers.

03:29.442 --> 03:31.211
Somebody picks a card,

03:31.244 --> 03:33.413
they put it back in the deck
after signing it.

03:33.446 --> 03:36.049
Amongst 51 other possibilities,

03:36.082 --> 03:38.818
the magician
always finds the card.

03:38.851 --> 03:40.920
Pretty amazing.
Pretty good odds.

03:40.954 --> 03:42.322
- Yes, sir.
- But not good enough

03:42.355 --> 03:44.557
for "Penn & Teller: Fool Us."

03:44.591 --> 03:48.695
Today my odds of success
aren't going to be one in 52,

03:48.728 --> 03:54.100
but rather one in 26,497

03:54.133 --> 03:56.069
Styrofoam packing peanuts.

03:56.102 --> 03:59.205
Four hundred and six--
four hundred and seven--

03:59.239 --> 04:00.707
seventy-two--
there's just a lot.

04:00.740 --> 04:02.542
There's a lot
of packing peanuts.

04:02.575 --> 04:05.044
Your honors,
may I approach the bench?

04:05.078 --> 04:08.681
[upbeat music]

04:08.715 --> 04:10.683
- Oh, this is great.

04:10.717 --> 04:13.353
- Oh, before I do,
nobody has a peanut allergy?

04:13.386 --> 04:14.554
- I d--
[laughs]

04:14.587 --> 04:16.055
- Okay.

04:17.923 --> 04:19.993
Teller, I'd like you
to please go ahead.

04:20.026 --> 04:22.395
Pick a peanut,
any peanut.

04:22.428 --> 04:24.330
That's great.
And with this pen,

04:24.364 --> 04:26.366
I'd like you to write
your favorite amendment

04:26.399 --> 04:29.235
from the Bill of Rights
on the peanut.

04:29.269 --> 04:31.371
Just initial both sides,
is fine.

04:31.404 --> 04:32.639
Thank you.
While they do that,

04:32.672 --> 04:35.975
Fabian, you and I
are going to mix this box.

04:36.009 --> 04:37.477
We're gonna lift it in the air.

04:37.510 --> 04:40.380
We shake it like this.
You can go like this, too.

04:40.413 --> 04:41.547
Like that.

04:41.581 --> 04:43.249
- Oh.
- Great. Place it down.

04:43.283 --> 04:45.018
Thank you very much.
You can have a seat.

04:45.051 --> 04:46.486
Teller, how is that
packing peanut going?

04:46.519 --> 04:47.587
Perfect.

04:47.620 --> 04:49.722
I don't want to touch it
with my hands.

04:49.756 --> 04:56.562
♪ ♪

04:58.097 --> 05:01.367
It is now time to reunite

05:01.401 --> 05:04.037
our poor lone packing peanut

05:04.070 --> 05:06.472
with its friends and family.

05:06.506 --> 05:11.678
♪ ♪

05:11.711 --> 05:13.279
Bye, little buddy.

05:13.313 --> 05:14.847
All right, Fabian,
here's the fun part.

05:14.881 --> 05:16.316
Let's mix this box up.

05:16.349 --> 05:18.151
Go ahead.
You can close your flap.

05:18.184 --> 05:19.285
That's great.

05:19.319 --> 05:20.787
How about now, Fabian?
Are you having fun?

05:20.820 --> 05:21.988
- A lot.
- Yeah, a lot now.

05:22.021 --> 05:24.023
That's great.
Okay, so take your right hand.

05:24.057 --> 05:25.725
Place it on top just like this.

05:25.758 --> 05:27.860
We're gonna lift the box up,
and now's our time to shine.

05:27.894 --> 05:28.995
Go ahead.
Shake it, Fabian.

05:29.028 --> 05:30.730
Shake it
like your mama gave you.

05:30.763 --> 05:31.964
Come on.
Put your back into it.

05:31.998 --> 05:33.333
Like this, Fabian.
- Oh.

05:33.366 --> 05:34.867
- Put your back into it.

05:34.901 --> 05:37.970
Your back into--like this--
upside down, upside down.

05:38.004 --> 05:39.505
Yeah.
- Okay.

05:39.539 --> 05:41.474
[laughter]

05:41.507 --> 05:42.742
- Thank you very much.

05:42.775 --> 05:44.077
Fabian, behind you,

05:44.110 --> 05:46.913
you will find rollers
with industrial-strength glue.

05:46.946 --> 05:48.181
- Uh-huh.
- I'd like you to go ahead

05:48.214 --> 05:50.049
and dip the rollers
into the glue.

05:50.083 --> 05:52.318
♪ ♪

05:52.352 --> 05:53.486
Perfect.

05:53.519 --> 05:55.321
Here's the fun part.

05:55.355 --> 05:58.358
You're going to douse me
in that glue.

05:58.391 --> 06:00.193
Let me show you how.

06:00.226 --> 06:02.762
Just like this.

06:02.795 --> 06:05.832
♪ ♪

06:05.865 --> 06:08.468
[audience oohs]

06:08.501 --> 06:10.503
♪ ♪

06:10.536 --> 06:14.273
Fabian, can you do my back?

06:14.307 --> 06:16.142
Just rub it in like sunscreen,
Fabian, yeah.

06:16.175 --> 06:19.212
You get in there.
You get in there.

06:19.245 --> 06:23.483
All the nooks
and crannies, buddy.

06:23.516 --> 06:24.684
Needless to say,
my parents

06:24.717 --> 06:26.519
are very proud
of my life choices.

06:26.552 --> 06:28.821
[laughter]

06:28.855 --> 06:31.724
All right, Fabian,
here's what's gonna happen.

06:31.758 --> 06:35.161
I'm gonna blindfold myself...

06:35.194 --> 06:36.562
and jump in that box.

06:36.596 --> 06:38.131
Ugh.

06:38.164 --> 06:40.500
Fabian, for right now,
you can go and have a seat.

06:40.533 --> 06:42.735
When I jump in the box,
the audience will join you,

06:42.769 --> 06:45.571
the nice countdown
from 20 to one.

06:45.605 --> 06:47.340
You're gonna start it for them.

06:47.373 --> 06:49.308
Everybody, Fabian...

06:49.342 --> 06:53.179
[cheers and applause]

06:53.212 --> 06:54.380
[exhales sharply]

06:54.414 --> 06:57.150
[chuckles]

06:57.183 --> 07:00.686
Here we go.

07:00.720 --> 07:03.623
all: 20, 19, 18,

07:03.656 --> 07:08.094
17, 16, 15, 14,

07:08.127 --> 07:11.364
13, 12, 11,

07:11.397 --> 07:14.467
ten, nine, eight,

07:14.500 --> 07:18.704
seven, six, five, four,

07:18.738 --> 07:21.941
three, two, one.

07:21.974 --> 07:24.777
[cheers and applause]

07:24.811 --> 07:27.847
[drumroll]

07:31.517 --> 07:33.653
[rim shot]

07:33.686 --> 07:36.489
[audience murmuring]

07:44.831 --> 07:46.866
[gulps]

07:54.373 --> 07:58.978
[cheers and applause]

07:59.011 --> 08:01.481
[laughter]

08:03.649 --> 08:06.285
- Eric LeClerc!

08:06.319 --> 08:10.022
[cheers and applause continue]

08:10.056 --> 08:13.025
Nice to air-meet you.

08:13.059 --> 08:15.862
This is a messy act
to practice.

08:15.895 --> 08:18.097
- Yeah. I mean, you guys have
people here to clean this up.

08:18.130 --> 08:20.199
- No, I know,
but at your house.

08:20.233 --> 08:21.434
- Yeah.

08:21.467 --> 08:23.369
- Like, do you practice
at your house

08:23.402 --> 08:25.204
will all these peanuts?
- I did practice this.

08:25.238 --> 08:26.672
It was a big mess.
Worth it, though.

08:26.706 --> 08:27.940
- Yes.
- Yeah.

08:27.974 --> 08:30.042
- Well, let's see
if the boys went nuts

08:30.076 --> 08:31.611
trying to solve your trick.

08:31.644 --> 08:33.011
Boys?

08:33.044 --> 08:34.981
- What a great routine.

08:35.014 --> 08:36.549
- Thank you.
- You know, we've been trying

08:36.582 --> 08:39.150
for, what, 30 years,

08:39.184 --> 08:42.822
to come up with a really good
needle-in-a-haystack routine

08:42.855 --> 08:44.190
and using a little bit--

08:44.222 --> 08:46.125
although not as well
as you did--

08:46.158 --> 08:48.227
a little bit of that premise,
needle in a haystack...

08:48.261 --> 08:49.695
- Right.
- Finding something impossible.

08:49.729 --> 08:51.163
- Yes.
- It's really, really good.

08:51.197 --> 08:54.800
And it's also great
to see someone

08:54.834 --> 08:57.737
who really understands
what this show is about.

08:57.770 --> 09:00.373
- Thank you so much.
- The show is called "Fool Us."

09:00.406 --> 09:03.509
But the real reason
for this show

09:03.543 --> 09:05.144
is for people to come on

09:05.177 --> 09:08.581
and do fabulous,
original magic...

09:08.614 --> 09:11.150
[applause]

09:11.183 --> 09:14.687
And be funny and entertaining
every step of the way.

09:14.720 --> 09:16.756
I have to ask you a question.

09:16.789 --> 09:20.426
Teller thought you had
some sort of container.

09:20.459 --> 09:21.961
We're not
gonna describe it exactly,

09:21.994 --> 09:25.097
but some sort of jar
or something

09:25.131 --> 09:29.635
that you carefully placed
the hero in,

09:29.669 --> 09:34.273
and I thought I remembered it
actually fluttering down.

09:34.307 --> 09:37.276
But did you place it--
was it carefully placed?

09:37.310 --> 09:40.479
- It was let go
at about right here.

09:40.513 --> 09:41.681
Just...

09:41.714 --> 09:44.016
- Okay, well,
like I said, Eric,

09:44.050 --> 09:46.052
the important part of the show

09:46.085 --> 09:48.387
is to do a really entertaining,

09:48.421 --> 09:51.057
wonderful piece
of innovative magic

09:51.090 --> 09:53.292
that the whole audience loves,

09:53.326 --> 09:56.028
and the part of the show
that doesn't matter

09:56.062 --> 09:58.230
nearly as much
is the fact that you fooled us.

09:58.264 --> 09:59.865
- Yeah!

09:59.899 --> 10:02.234
[cheers and applause]

10:02.268 --> 10:04.303
Can I shake your hand?

10:04.337 --> 10:06.305
- Really great job.
Really great.

10:06.339 --> 10:08.140
- Oh, I was so scared you
were gonna hug me.

10:08.174 --> 10:11.210
[cheers and applause continue]

10:12.411 --> 10:15.247
Yay!

10:15.281 --> 10:19.251
Whoo! Eric LeClerc!

10:19.285 --> 10:21.020
- Oh, my God.

10:21.053 --> 10:24.523
- Thank you!

10:24.557 --> 10:26.225
Whoo-hoo!

10:28.294 --> 10:30.696
I thought Penn and Teller
knew every trick in the book,

10:30.730 --> 10:32.999
but looks like
they skipped a page.

10:33.032 --> 10:35.001
We'll let them
study up during the break.

10:35.034 --> 10:36.769
Stay close.

10:36.802 --> 10:39.605
[cheers and applause]

10:44.644 --> 10:46.846
[jazz music]

10:46.879 --> 10:49.582
[cheers and applause]

10:49.615 --> 10:50.916
- Welcome back.

10:50.950 --> 10:52.385
If you're just joining us,

10:52.418 --> 10:54.887
you missed Penn and Teller
getting fooled.

10:54.920 --> 10:57.590
Maybe you can see it
happen again with our next act.

11:00.226 --> 11:02.028
- I started doing magic
to get girls.

11:02.061 --> 11:06.699
As a teenager,
I was bedeviled by insecurity,

11:06.732 --> 11:10.302
and I wondered what would make
the opposite sex admire me.

11:10.336 --> 11:12.672
Then a friend of mine
made a toothpick disappear,

11:12.705 --> 11:15.341
and it totally freaked me out.

11:15.374 --> 11:17.543
He showed me the method,
and it seemed doable.

11:17.576 --> 11:19.679
Playing around
with illusions changed me.

11:19.712 --> 11:21.213
To perform takes confidence,

11:21.247 --> 11:23.049
so I had to find
some inside me.

11:23.082 --> 11:24.483
I tried out for "Fool Us"

11:24.517 --> 11:26.419
because I met
a famous magician,

11:26.452 --> 11:29.855
and he told me that I wasn't
good enough to be on the show.

11:29.889 --> 11:31.424
So I worked hard

11:31.457 --> 11:34.860
on an original illusion,
and, amazingly...

11:34.894 --> 11:36.429
I'm here.

11:36.462 --> 11:38.230
I'm still
terribly afraid at times.

11:38.264 --> 11:41.667
I constantly move
between joy and self-doubt.

11:41.701 --> 11:43.035
Which will win out?

11:43.069 --> 11:44.704
[chuckles]
I guess we're about to see.

11:44.737 --> 11:47.606
Tonight on "Fool Us," I will
hurl myself into the abyss,

11:47.640 --> 11:50.076
and hopefully my magic
will catch me.

11:50.109 --> 11:52.011
[applause]

11:52.044 --> 11:55.381
- Here with a randomly
pre-selected host of the show

11:55.414 --> 11:57.717
is Dev Sherman!

11:57.750 --> 12:00.553
[cheers and applause]

12:03.022 --> 12:06.859
- I feel like
I'm standing in a dream...

12:06.892 --> 12:09.562
an absolutely incredible dream.

12:09.595 --> 12:11.864
I can't believe that
I get to show a magic trick

12:11.897 --> 12:14.667
in front of two of the greatest
magicians alive.

12:14.700 --> 12:16.469
I can't--I can't believe it.

12:16.502 --> 12:17.970
- Aw.
- [laughs]

12:18.003 --> 12:21.841
[cheers and applause]

12:21.874 --> 12:23.476
I never thought
that I was actually good enough

12:23.509 --> 12:25.044
to be here.

12:25.077 --> 12:27.046
Never.
[dramatic tone]

12:27.079 --> 12:29.482
- That's because
you're not good enough.

12:29.515 --> 12:32.084
You're just an average,
ordinary magician.

12:32.118 --> 12:33.385
Look at your suit.

12:33.419 --> 12:37.056
There's a stain
on your pocket square.

12:37.089 --> 12:38.324
- [sighs]
Sorry about that.

12:38.357 --> 12:42.528
That's the voice
of my inner critic.

12:42.561 --> 12:46.198
Um, he gets really
annoying and loud,

12:46.232 --> 12:47.867
especially when
I'm about to do magic, right?

12:47.900 --> 12:50.102
And sometimes--
Hold on.

12:50.136 --> 12:51.704
If I just...

12:51.737 --> 12:54.106
do that.

12:54.140 --> 12:55.674
No more stain.
- Ahh.

12:55.708 --> 12:58.277
- Thank you.

12:58.310 --> 13:00.880
Yeah, sometimes
I can't keep him quiet.

13:00.913 --> 13:02.515
So what I do is I draw.

13:02.548 --> 13:03.849
- Oh.
- I draw symbols

13:03.883 --> 13:06.786
that have a magical effect
on me, right?

13:06.819 --> 13:09.121
First I draw waves.

13:09.155 --> 13:12.658
Let me show you.
Let me show you what I draw.

13:12.691 --> 13:13.959
First, I draw waves.
Can you see that?

13:13.993 --> 13:15.961
Yeah, perfect.

13:15.995 --> 13:17.396
[exhales sharply]

13:17.429 --> 13:19.865
Waves because they remind me
to breathe, right?

13:19.899 --> 13:21.634
Like, they rise and fall.
They remind me to breathe in...

13:21.667 --> 13:23.569
[inhales deeply]

13:23.602 --> 13:27.306
- [breathing deeply]

13:27.339 --> 13:28.407
- And breathe out.
[exhales deeply]

13:28.440 --> 13:30.810
- Oh.
- [laughs]

13:30.843 --> 13:32.478
That's fine.
- Okay.

13:32.511 --> 13:33.913
- It calms me down, right?

13:33.946 --> 13:37.249
And then we draw a fish hook.

13:37.283 --> 13:38.551
[exhales sharply]
Fish hook.

13:38.584 --> 13:39.752
- Oh.
- A fish hook

13:39.785 --> 13:42.188
signifies strength
and determination.

13:42.221 --> 13:43.489
So every time I draw it,

13:43.522 --> 13:45.925
I feel stronger
and more determined.

13:45.958 --> 13:47.693
- Okay.
- And then finally

13:47.726 --> 13:51.831
I draw the lotus.

13:51.864 --> 13:53.265
The lotus...
[exhales sharply]

13:53.299 --> 13:55.201
Signifies purity.

13:55.234 --> 13:57.203
[exhales sharply]
Purity because it grows

13:57.236 --> 14:00.406
in these dark, dirty,
muddy conditions,

14:00.439 --> 14:02.341
but it blooms
into this beautiful flower.

14:02.374 --> 14:04.043
So it makes me feel like,

14:04.076 --> 14:07.780
even though my inner critic
is clearly not very nice to me,

14:07.813 --> 14:10.049
I can still do
beautiful magic...

14:10.082 --> 14:11.517
like this.

14:11.550 --> 14:14.954
So we have one,
two, three, four cards,

14:14.987 --> 14:17.323
and one of them
has symbols on them.

14:17.356 --> 14:20.159
But if I wave...

14:21.493 --> 14:24.129
This printed to two cards.

14:24.163 --> 14:27.633
If I wave again...

14:27.666 --> 14:30.369
now they're on three.

14:30.402 --> 14:32.304
And one more time...

14:32.338 --> 14:34.874
One, two, three, four.

14:34.907 --> 14:36.508
Every card.

14:36.542 --> 14:37.843
One, two, three--
[dramatic tone]

14:37.877 --> 14:40.546
- That's not beautiful magic.

14:40.579 --> 14:43.115
It's only four cards.

14:45.417 --> 14:47.219
- Let's do more, then.
Let's do more.

14:47.253 --> 14:49.355
Why not, right?
If not four, then more.

14:49.388 --> 14:52.224
Right, all it takes,
all I have to do...

14:52.258 --> 14:56.662
is spread,
take one of these,

14:56.695 --> 14:58.697
do a fancy thing,

14:58.731 --> 15:01.133
and wave.

15:01.166 --> 15:03.269
Do you want to wave as well?
- Hey.

15:03.302 --> 15:04.470
- Very magical.
- Nice.

15:04.503 --> 15:05.604
- Good job.
[laughs]

15:05.638 --> 15:07.606
All right, everybody,
breathe in.

15:07.640 --> 15:10.175
[inhales deeply]

15:10.209 --> 15:12.378
[exhales deeply]

15:12.411 --> 15:14.313
- Wow!

15:14.346 --> 15:17.149
[cheers and applause]

15:20.519 --> 15:21.820
- Let's try--
let's try one more thing.

15:21.854 --> 15:23.889
Can you make a cup
with your hands?

15:23.923 --> 15:25.124
All right, see,
if I give the symbols--

15:25.157 --> 15:26.225
It doesn't work every time,

15:26.258 --> 15:29.028
but if I give
the symbols a rub...

15:29.061 --> 15:32.464
they come off.

15:32.498 --> 15:34.466
Give them a shake.
Shake them in your hands.

15:34.500 --> 15:35.668
Shake them.
Yeah, nice.

15:35.701 --> 15:37.036
Good shaking.
Well done.

15:37.069 --> 15:38.971
All right, so you've got
the symbols in your hand,

15:39.004 --> 15:41.540
and I have a few more cards
without any symbols on them.

15:41.573 --> 15:43.809
Right? Have a look
and just name any one of these.

15:43.842 --> 15:46.245
- Uh, five of diamonds.

15:46.278 --> 15:47.546
- Five of diamonds?
Perfect, all right.

15:47.579 --> 15:49.248
Think about the fish hook.

15:49.281 --> 15:51.050
With strength
and determination,

15:51.083 --> 15:53.085
throw the symbols
onto the five of diamonds.

15:53.118 --> 15:54.653
One, two, three.

15:54.687 --> 15:57.022
[magical whoosh]

15:57.056 --> 15:59.725
[exhales sharply]

15:59.758 --> 16:02.828
Only one card.

16:02.861 --> 16:05.197
Only one card
has the symbols on them.

16:05.230 --> 16:06.966
And you named a specific card.

16:06.999 --> 16:08.200
What was it,
the five of diamonds?

16:08.233 --> 16:09.835
- Mm-hmm.
- And you just named it, right?

16:09.868 --> 16:11.203
- Just named it.
- Yeah.

16:11.236 --> 16:13.172
- Yeah.
- The five of--

16:14.573 --> 16:17.443
[dramatic tone]
- I told you.

16:17.476 --> 16:20.145
I told you
you couldn't do it.

16:20.179 --> 16:23.115
You don't belong here.

16:23.148 --> 16:26.652
- [panting]

16:26.685 --> 16:27.886
[sighs]

16:27.920 --> 16:30.522
Five of diamonds?

16:30.556 --> 16:32.024
Five of diamonds.

16:32.057 --> 16:33.726
- Wow.

16:33.759 --> 16:35.861
[cheers and applause]

16:35.894 --> 16:40.232
Dev Sherman,
ladies and gentlemen!

16:40.265 --> 16:42.167
Wow.

16:42.201 --> 16:44.036
Aw. I don't think
you should ever listen

16:44.069 --> 16:45.304
to that voice again.

16:45.337 --> 16:46.872
- Okay, thank you.
- I was really touched

16:46.905 --> 16:49.208
by how excited you are

16:49.241 --> 16:50.843
to perform
in front of Penn and Teller.

16:50.876 --> 16:53.679
- Yeah, I didn't ever imagine
I'd be here.

16:53.712 --> 16:56.081
My God, I can't believe it,
so--I still can't believe it.

16:56.115 --> 16:58.484
[both laughing]

16:58.517 --> 17:00.686
- So what is your favorite
performance ever,

17:00.719 --> 17:01.520
besides this one?

17:01.553 --> 17:02.788
- Oh, okay.

17:02.821 --> 17:04.522
So, when I was in university,

17:04.556 --> 17:07.626
I went to Nepal
with a bunch of other students,

17:07.659 --> 17:09.028
and I started showing magic

17:09.060 --> 17:11.964
to, like, a few kids
over there, and they loved it.

17:11.997 --> 17:13.665
And I couldn't speak
a word of theirs,

17:13.699 --> 17:16.035
and they couldn't speak, like,
a word of mine--of my language.

17:16.068 --> 17:18.470
And yet everyone loved it.
Everyone reacted.

17:18.503 --> 17:20.271
It was a really
special performance.

17:20.305 --> 17:22.441
- Oh, I can only imagine.
- Yeah.

17:22.473 --> 17:24.777
- All right, it's time
to find out if Penn and Teller

17:24.810 --> 17:27.311
know how you did your trick.
- All right, great.

17:27.346 --> 17:28.614
- Hey, Dev.
- Hi.

17:28.647 --> 17:30.449
- Boy, really nice.

17:30.482 --> 17:32.217
You did that thing
we love in magic

17:32.251 --> 17:36.288
where you do three sections
that look like

17:36.321 --> 17:39.458
they're the same subject,
same plot, same ideas,

17:39.491 --> 17:41.193
but totally different methods,

17:41.226 --> 17:43.028
and that's always
a really good way to fool.

17:43.062 --> 17:45.464
- Yeah.
- And there's a--

17:45.497 --> 17:47.199
I think you are familiar

17:47.232 --> 17:50.369
with our good friends
Count Elmsley--

17:50.402 --> 17:51.570
- Oh, yeah, absolutely.
- I think you've heard of him.

17:51.603 --> 17:53.906
And Señor Asconio,
I think you've also--

17:53.939 --> 17:55.374
- Yeah, I know him as well.

17:55.407 --> 17:56.742
- You probably--
two of our friends

17:56.775 --> 17:58.577
you've bumped into
now and again.

17:58.610 --> 18:02.481
- Lovely people.
- And there was a symmetry

18:02.514 --> 18:04.450
to your act and the way
things were laid out

18:04.483 --> 18:07.419
that was really beautiful,
the way it comes back in,

18:07.453 --> 18:11.290
and the idea of the inner
critic was very good.

18:11.323 --> 18:13.492
You're very rough on yourself
with the inner critic.

18:13.525 --> 18:14.760
- [laughs]
- But then it was

18:14.793 --> 18:16.428
a smooth performance
all the way through.

18:16.462 --> 18:18.797
- Cool, thank you.
- Really, really, really nice

18:18.831 --> 18:20.299
and a really nice idea.

18:20.332 --> 18:21.967
And we hope in all of that

18:22.000 --> 18:24.036
that we gave you enough
slid in there.

18:24.069 --> 18:25.270
I don't want to give away--
- Oh, yeah, totally.

18:25.304 --> 18:26.672
- Oh, good, good, good.
- Absolutely.

18:26.705 --> 18:28.674
- So you didn't fool them.
- Nah, I didn't fool them.

18:28.707 --> 18:31.477
- Oh, well, thank you so much.
Dev Sherman!

18:31.510 --> 18:33.011
- Thank you.

18:33.045 --> 18:36.849
[cheers and applause]

18:36.882 --> 18:40.185
- Up next, Penn and Teller
take on more magic tricks.

18:40.219 --> 18:43.222
And later, Penn and Teller
perform one of their very own.

18:43.255 --> 18:44.490
Stick around.

18:44.523 --> 18:47.326
[applause]

18:52.364 --> 18:54.399
[jazz music]

18:54.433 --> 18:57.236
[cheers and applause]

18:57.269 --> 18:58.704
- Welcome back.

18:58.737 --> 19:00.839
It's time
for another amazing magician.

19:00.873 --> 19:02.040
Take a look.

19:28.367 --> 19:29.568
[laughs]

19:51.089 --> 19:55.794
[cheers and applause]

19:55.827 --> 19:58.897
Please welcome Conan Liu!

19:58.931 --> 20:02.000
[cheers and applause]

20:03.202 --> 20:04.469
- Hello, guys.

20:04.503 --> 20:07.339
My name is Conan Liu,
and I'm from China.

20:07.372 --> 20:09.508
Growing up,
my dad always tells me,

20:09.541 --> 20:12.177
"A cup of tea a day
keeps the doctor away."

20:12.211 --> 20:15.380
China's tea
is very good for health

20:15.414 --> 20:19.718
because it's originated
from the natural tea leaves.

20:19.751 --> 20:22.054
But modern people
will also mix in...

20:22.087 --> 20:23.488
a tea bag,

20:23.522 --> 20:25.357
which is convenient
and portable.

20:25.390 --> 20:26.758
Alyson,
do you want to check it out?

20:26.792 --> 20:28.327
- Sure.
- Ladies and gentlemen, Alyson!

20:28.360 --> 20:29.728
- Oh, thanks.

20:29.761 --> 20:31.163
- Hello, Alyson.

20:31.196 --> 20:32.431
- Hi.
- Give it a touch.

20:32.464 --> 20:33.599
- Does it--does it--
- Yeah?

20:33.632 --> 20:34.833
It feels like
a real tea bag, right?

20:34.866 --> 20:36.068
- Absolutely.

20:36.101 --> 20:38.270
- And I'm gonna
go back to it later.

20:38.303 --> 20:39.871
I'm gonna place it right here.

20:39.905 --> 20:41.273
You know what, Alyson?

20:41.306 --> 20:44.076
To make a cup of tea,
we'll need a container,

20:44.109 --> 20:46.078
which is...

20:46.111 --> 20:47.212
a teapot.

20:47.246 --> 20:48.780
- Oh.
- Clear and clean.

20:48.814 --> 20:50.282
Can you do me a favor, Alyson?

20:50.315 --> 20:52.251
Show your right hand like this.

20:52.284 --> 20:54.453
And hold it like this.

20:54.486 --> 20:56.588
- Okay.
- Firmly, and don't move.

20:56.622 --> 20:57.756
And you know what?

20:57.789 --> 21:00.559
We'll also need some
purified drinking water.

21:00.592 --> 21:01.860
- Oh.
- [laughs]

21:01.893 --> 21:04.563
And...
Just be careful.

21:04.596 --> 21:07.032
I'm gonna pour the water
into the teapot like this.

21:07.065 --> 21:09.067
- Okay.
- And--

21:09.101 --> 21:10.836
All right,
let's give it a try.

21:10.869 --> 21:12.471
Can you tilt it a little?

21:12.504 --> 21:13.972
Yeah.

21:14.006 --> 21:15.540
Okay, it's water, right?

21:15.574 --> 21:18.677
- Yes.
- It's water, okay.

21:18.710 --> 21:21.046
Tastes good.

21:21.079 --> 21:23.115
And check this out--
the tea bag...

21:24.783 --> 21:26.351
Watch.

21:26.385 --> 21:29.354
[dramatic music]

21:29.388 --> 21:32.491
♪ ♪

21:32.524 --> 21:34.226
- Whoa!

21:34.259 --> 21:35.594
[applause]

21:35.627 --> 21:37.729
- Alyson, you know what?
I will take this for you.

21:37.763 --> 21:41.433
This is for you.

21:41.466 --> 21:43.268
It looks like tea.
You can smell it.

21:43.302 --> 21:44.569
Does it smell like tea?
- Yes.

21:44.603 --> 21:45.704
- It smells like tea.

21:45.737 --> 21:47.773
You can take a sip.

21:49.574 --> 21:51.009
Is it tea?
- Yes, it's good tea.

21:51.043 --> 21:52.377
- It is tea!
Ladies and gentlemen, Alyson!

21:52.411 --> 21:54.279
- That's amazing!

21:54.313 --> 21:58.583
[cheers and applause]

21:58.617 --> 22:01.386
- Thank you, but that's just
a gift for Alyson.

22:01.420 --> 22:03.322
I still have a gift
for everybody here,

22:03.355 --> 22:05.657
including Penn and Teller,
my heroes.

22:05.691 --> 22:07.125
You know what?

22:07.159 --> 22:09.461
Tonight I'm gonna show you
the real essence

22:09.494 --> 22:11.897
of Chinese tea culture

22:11.930 --> 22:16.501
with this branch of...
tea leaves.

22:16.535 --> 22:18.670
Check this out.
Follow me.

22:18.704 --> 22:21.473
♪ ♪

22:21.506 --> 22:23.809
I'm gonna place
this branch of tea leaves

22:23.842 --> 22:26.478
onto the table like this.

22:26.511 --> 22:29.881
As you can see,
there's nothing above,

22:29.915 --> 22:34.686
nothing beneath,
nothing anywhere.

22:34.720 --> 22:36.188
Check this out.

22:36.221 --> 22:38.256
Ladies and gentlemen,
this is gonna be

22:38.290 --> 22:41.693
where the real magic happens.

22:41.727 --> 22:43.061
Watch.

22:43.095 --> 22:50.135
♪ ♪

22:51.903 --> 22:53.271
Go!

22:53.305 --> 23:00.112
♪ ♪

23:07.219 --> 23:10.455
Ladies and gentlemen, meet
my new friend, the tea girl...

23:10.489 --> 23:13.392
Nikki!

23:13.425 --> 23:17.062
[cheers and applause]

23:30.075 --> 23:32.644
- Conan Liu!

23:32.677 --> 23:33.645
- Wow.

23:33.678 --> 23:35.046
- That was wonderful.

23:35.080 --> 23:37.149
- Thank you.
- And really good tea.

23:37.182 --> 23:38.483
- [laughs]
both: Thank you.

23:38.517 --> 23:40.719
- So tell me about this trick.

23:40.752 --> 23:43.889
- We have been working on this
for the last three months.

23:43.922 --> 23:46.158
- That seems short.

23:46.191 --> 23:47.359
- It's very hard,
but the good thing is that

23:47.392 --> 23:50.195
I have done
a lot of TV shows in China,

23:50.228 --> 23:53.064
and that's
a kind of advantage for me.

23:53.098 --> 23:54.766
But this
is my first time to appear

23:54.800 --> 23:56.568
on the U.S. television.

23:56.601 --> 23:57.903
- Oh.

23:57.936 --> 23:59.604
Welcome to "Fool Us."

23:59.638 --> 24:00.872
[applause]
- Thank you.

24:00.906 --> 24:03.842
- Thank you for coming.

24:03.875 --> 24:06.178
And you do a lot of magic
on social media.

24:06.211 --> 24:07.446
- Yeah, I do a lot.

24:07.479 --> 24:10.048
You have to get your audience
from social media,

24:10.081 --> 24:11.683
not just from TV.

24:11.716 --> 24:14.319
- Ah. Well, I'm gonna
have to start following you.

24:14.352 --> 24:15.620
- [laughs]
- Okay.

24:15.654 --> 24:17.722
Let's find out if you fooled
Penn and Teller.

24:17.756 --> 24:19.224
- Oh, my goodness, Conan.

24:19.257 --> 24:22.961
That was just beautiful,
just beautiful.

24:22.994 --> 24:26.231
Really, really great
and simple and stark

24:26.264 --> 24:29.067
and did not look
at all magic prop-y.

24:29.100 --> 24:31.303
To people at home,

24:31.336 --> 24:34.639
probably the appearance
of the person

24:34.673 --> 24:36.975
at the end
was the mind-blower.

24:37.008 --> 24:40.579
And that was beautiful
and perfect and wonderful...

24:40.612 --> 24:42.581
but didn't fool us that deeply.

24:42.614 --> 24:44.549
- Yeah.
- It's that teapot.

24:44.583 --> 24:47.986
Man, turning that into tea
was incredible.

24:48.019 --> 24:50.021
Not that big a deal

24:50.055 --> 24:53.225
if Alyson couldn't smell it

24:53.258 --> 24:55.193
and drink it and taste it.

24:55.227 --> 24:57.529
Lot of poisonous ways
to do that.

24:57.562 --> 25:00.065
[laughter]

25:00.098 --> 25:01.366
Which--
- Now you tell me.

25:01.399 --> 25:02.834
- Right.

25:02.868 --> 25:04.936
And I'll tell you on this one,

25:04.970 --> 25:06.471
it's another one
of those situations

25:06.505 --> 25:09.975
where it's a two-person act,

25:10.008 --> 25:13.111
and I was convinced

25:13.144 --> 25:15.680
that it was somehow
a gimmick teapot.

25:15.714 --> 25:17.549
I did not know how,

25:17.582 --> 25:19.518
but I thought you'd done
something with the teapot,

25:19.551 --> 25:23.021
and Teller is the one
that was steadfast

25:23.054 --> 25:25.557
in saying that the teapot
was completely innocent.

25:25.590 --> 25:27.158
And I will tell you,

25:27.192 --> 25:30.128
because I want to give away
as little as possible,

25:30.161 --> 25:34.866
that in comedy, timing,
they say, is everything.

25:34.900 --> 25:37.969
In magic,
and especially in this trick,

25:38.003 --> 25:41.006
timing really was everything.

25:41.039 --> 25:44.709
Timing is your misdirection.
Timing is your surprise.

25:44.743 --> 25:46.177
Timing is everything.

25:46.211 --> 25:48.713
And you had
that timing with just...

25:48.747 --> 25:50.081
like a snap of a finger.

25:50.115 --> 25:52.884
It was just amazing
and perfect.

25:52.918 --> 25:54.152
And if you just know

25:54.185 --> 25:56.855
what I'm talking
about on the timing,

25:56.888 --> 25:58.823
maybe we're okay--
we think we've got it.

25:58.857 --> 25:59.824
- Do you--
- I think

25:59.858 --> 26:01.326
I may need more details.

26:01.359 --> 26:03.795
- Okay,
why don't we go to the judges?

26:03.828 --> 26:05.530
They are in Alyson's ear.

26:05.564 --> 26:08.433
- All right, they know how
all the tricks are done.

26:08.466 --> 26:09.968
- Okay.
- And they know everything

26:10.001 --> 26:11.303
that Penn and Teller say.

26:11.336 --> 26:12.370
- Uh-huh.

26:12.404 --> 26:15.273
- And they're telling
me that...

26:15.307 --> 26:17.375
you did not fool
Penn and Teller.

26:17.409 --> 26:20.011
- But it's my great pleasure.
- Aw.

26:20.045 --> 26:21.846
- You were great.
- But you were so wonderful.

26:21.880 --> 26:23.949
Conan Liu!

26:23.982 --> 26:24.683
[cheers and applause]

26:24.716 --> 26:27.686
Thank you!

26:29.721 --> 26:32.223
Penn and Teller will attempt
to figure out another trick

26:32.257 --> 26:34.693
before performing
one of their own,

26:34.726 --> 26:36.561
all coming up after this.

26:36.595 --> 26:39.397
[cheers and applause]

26:44.436 --> 26:46.905
[jazz music]

26:46.938 --> 26:49.541
[cheers and applause]

26:49.574 --> 26:50.709
- Welcome back.

26:50.742 --> 26:53.211
Let's meet
our next potential fooler.

26:55.580 --> 26:58.650
- I'm Ruben Vilagrand,
and I come from Spain.

26:58.683 --> 26:59.884
I live in Europe.

26:59.918 --> 27:01.653
My audience speaks
many languages

27:01.686 --> 27:04.522
because they came from many,
many different countries.

27:04.556 --> 27:07.325
Myself, I speak English,
French, and Spanish.

27:07.359 --> 27:09.160
But when you do
a gag in English,

27:09.194 --> 27:10.929
the French people,
they were like, "Huh?

27:10.962 --> 27:12.697
I don't get it."
[laughs]

27:12.731 --> 27:15.133
And then the Spanish people
were like...

27:15.166 --> 27:16.701
I don't want to use words

27:16.735 --> 27:18.770
because it breaks
the rhythm of my show.

27:18.803 --> 27:21.473
So I started to mime my magic,

27:21.506 --> 27:23.174
and everybody can understand
at the same time.

27:23.208 --> 27:25.977
By doing mime, my magic
became really powerful.

27:26.011 --> 27:27.646
And I can perform
all over the world

27:27.679 --> 27:28.780
in any language.

27:28.813 --> 27:30.482
[crack]
Ow.

27:30.515 --> 27:32.050
For ten years
performing this trick,

27:32.083 --> 27:33.318
I fool every magician,

27:33.351 --> 27:36.488
but will I fool
Penn and Teller?

27:36.521 --> 27:38.857
Who knows?
[laughs]

27:38.890 --> 27:42.827
[cheers and applause]

27:42.861 --> 27:47.532
- Please welcome Spanish
sorcerer Ruben Vilagrand!

27:47.565 --> 27:50.535
[cheers and applause]

27:50.568 --> 27:53.538
[quirky music]

27:53.571 --> 28:00.378
