Ruben Vilagrand!

31:07.098 --> 31:09.000
Ah!

31:09.033 --> 31:10.869
Hi!
- Hi!

31:10.902 --> 31:13.738
- So you know Teller does
a trick sort of like this.

31:13.771 --> 31:15.907
Is that extra pressure on you?

31:15.940 --> 31:17.675
- It is because
he is performing this trick

31:17.709 --> 31:18.843
before I was born.

31:18.877 --> 31:20.345
- Oh.
[laughter]

31:20.378 --> 31:21.746
[groans]

31:21.779 --> 31:24.649
So did this trick
take a long time to prepare?

31:24.682 --> 31:26.684
- Actually, yeah, it took me
a couple of years to create

31:26.718 --> 31:29.487
because the technique
is totally new.

31:29.520 --> 31:32.891
- So it's new.
Then maybe you will fool them.

31:32.924 --> 31:35.360
[laughter]
Aw.

31:35.393 --> 31:36.828
All right,
shall we see

31:36.861 --> 31:39.063
if Penn and Teller
swallowed the hook?

31:39.097 --> 31:40.565
[squeals]

31:40.598 --> 31:42.267
- That was great.
That was great, man.

31:42.300 --> 31:46.571
A lot of--as you know,
a lot of great, great magicians

31:46.604 --> 31:49.841
have done
the East Indian trick

31:49.874 --> 31:51.109
of swallowing needles.

31:51.142 --> 31:53.177
Some of the greatest
magicians in history--

31:53.211 --> 31:54.946
of course, Harry Houdini,

31:54.979 --> 31:57.749
and then if we want to build
above Harry Houdini...

31:57.782 --> 32:00.118
Teller...
- Aw.

32:00.151 --> 32:01.486
- Swallowed the needles.

32:01.519 --> 32:04.455
But fish hooks
is a really good idea.

32:04.489 --> 32:08.159
It also seems like you can't do

32:08.192 --> 32:10.528
the move with those
that you did.

32:10.561 --> 32:12.230
[laughs]

32:12.263 --> 32:15.133
It really--
the way the geometry works

32:15.166 --> 32:17.502
makes it much more deceptive
with fish hooks,

32:17.535 --> 32:19.337
not more deceptive than you,
of course.

32:19.370 --> 32:20.738
I wouldn't say that,

32:20.772 --> 32:23.408
but more deceptive than other
people doing the needles.

32:23.441 --> 32:24.475
That was great.

32:24.509 --> 32:28.313
So we know
how the needles is done,

32:28.346 --> 32:31.082
and we can map that
onto the fish hooks.

32:31.115 --> 32:32.483
Now, this is part of this thing

32:32.517 --> 32:35.186
where the show
gets rather esoteric

32:35.219 --> 32:38.323
because what we care about
is not what everybody else

32:38.356 --> 32:40.491
watching the show
will care about.

32:40.525 --> 32:43.261
They care about, whoa,
Ruben swallowed fish hooks,

32:43.294 --> 32:45.897
swallowed thread,
brought the fish hooks up

32:45.930 --> 32:47.332
on the thread.

32:47.365 --> 32:49.033
Wow, that was something.

32:49.067 --> 32:51.202
And, of course,
that is something,

32:51.235 --> 32:53.404
but our problem
is all with the thread.

32:53.438 --> 32:55.606
We thought
swallowing the thread

32:55.640 --> 32:57.675
was the really hard part.

32:57.709 --> 33:01.045
There's a part there with
the thread that does not fit

33:01.079 --> 33:03.715
in the way that we knew
this is done normally.

33:03.748 --> 33:05.817
That was the part
that blew our minds.

33:05.850 --> 33:07.218
And that made us think,

33:07.251 --> 33:09.287
"What do you need
to go fishing?"

33:09.320 --> 33:11.823
Well, you need
very unfashionable pants,

33:11.856 --> 33:13.157
and you need boots,

33:13.191 --> 33:16.127
and then you need
a rod and a reel.

33:16.160 --> 33:18.229
You need all those things
to go fishing.

33:18.262 --> 33:20.198
And as soon
as we thought about this

33:20.231 --> 33:22.166
with the fish hooks
and fishing,

33:22.200 --> 33:25.737
we thought we might
have a slight inkling

33:25.770 --> 33:27.839
as to how you did
the part of the trick

33:27.872 --> 33:29.340
that blew our minds,

33:29.374 --> 33:32.910
which was how you took it
right onto that reel of thread,

33:32.944 --> 33:34.679
the spool of thread.
- Yep.

33:34.712 --> 33:37.582
[laughter]

33:37.615 --> 33:40.485
[applause]

33:40.518 --> 33:42.220
- Well, I guess
you didn't fool them,

33:42.253 --> 33:44.389
but you certainly
entertained them.

33:44.422 --> 33:46.824
- Thank you!
- Thank you, Ruben Vilagrand!

33:46.858 --> 33:50.928
[cheers and applause]

33:50.962 --> 33:52.897
Don't go anywhere,
because if you do,

33:52.930 --> 33:54.766
you'll miss
something spectacular.

33:54.799 --> 33:56.768
More "Fool Us" in a moment.

33:56.801 --> 33:59.604
[cheers and applause]

34:04.675 --> 34:06.844
[jazz music]

34:06.878 --> 34:09.047
[cheers and applause]

34:09.080 --> 34:10.947
- Welcome back to "Fool Us."

34:10.982 --> 34:14.018
We've got something
very special for you up next.

34:14.052 --> 34:18.121
This magician normally performs
as part of a magic duo,

34:18.156 --> 34:20.291
but tonight
he thought it would be fun

34:20.324 --> 34:23.327
to surprise his partner
by performing alone.

34:23.360 --> 34:27.532
Ladies and gentlemen,
give it up for Penn Jillette!

34:27.565 --> 34:30.400
[cheers and applause]
- Me?

34:30.435 --> 34:33.670
Well, I-I do happen to have
a deck of cards.

34:33.704 --> 34:35.706
Uh, I...

34:35.739 --> 34:37.675
I happen to have
a deck of card--

34:37.708 --> 34:40.844
I guess I could give it a try
to fool you.

34:40.878 --> 34:44.081
Just kind of one-on-one.
Would you like that?

34:44.114 --> 34:47.051
Why don't you come up here
and have a sit-down right here?

34:47.085 --> 34:49.152
Would you, please?
And I'm...

34:49.187 --> 34:51.255
[applause]

34:51.289 --> 34:54.324
Have yourself--have yourself
a seat right there.

34:54.358 --> 34:57.161
I have a deck of cards
right here,

34:57.195 --> 34:59.497
and I'm gonna do
a couple things.

34:59.530 --> 35:03.434
This shuffle
is for the people at home.

35:03.468 --> 35:06.804
And this cut
is for the people at home.

35:06.838 --> 35:09.373
But you, what I'd like you
to do is now very carefully--

35:09.407 --> 35:11.342
follow the directions
very carefully.

35:11.375 --> 35:14.445
Just give those cards
a cut wherever you want

35:14.479 --> 35:17.648
and then complete the cut.

35:17.682 --> 35:19.217
And then complete the cut.

35:19.250 --> 35:20.952
Now, here's what I'm gonna do--

35:20.985 --> 35:23.387
it's a little procedural
on this, okay?

35:23.421 --> 35:25.857
I'm gonna take the cards
that you just cut,

35:25.890 --> 35:27.024
and I'm gonna turn my back.

35:27.058 --> 35:28.626
And I really won't look
at anything.

35:28.659 --> 35:30.128
I'll spread them out like this.

35:30.161 --> 35:34.031
And then just take one card,
look at it yourself,

35:34.065 --> 35:36.367
Don't show it to anyone.

35:36.400 --> 35:38.870
Memorize it,
put it in your vest pocket,

35:38.903 --> 35:40.738
the left vest pocket.

35:40.771 --> 35:44.475
And then gather them up again
nice and cleanly.

35:44.509 --> 35:47.245
And give them one cut
and complete the cut.

35:47.278 --> 35:51.315
And when you've done that,
give me a couple knocks there.

35:51.349 --> 35:52.750
Oh, good, good, good.

35:52.783 --> 35:54.585
Now, what you're gonna do

35:54.619 --> 35:56.921
is you're gonna take
your jacket off, please.

35:56.954 --> 35:58.322
Take your jacket off.

35:58.356 --> 36:00.825
And then you're gonna lay
that jacket

36:00.858 --> 36:02.927
right over my hands here.

36:02.960 --> 36:05.163
This way, just like that.

36:05.196 --> 36:09.700
Now, I'll tell you the premise
of this trick right now, okay?

36:09.734 --> 36:13.004
The premise of this trick
is based on exaggeration.

36:13.037 --> 36:14.872
You know that
I exaggerate an awful lot.

36:14.906 --> 36:17.275
I exaggerate
more than anybody in the world.

36:17.308 --> 36:20.978
So I'm kind of rounding up
our experiences on this show

36:21.012 --> 36:23.314
because you are the brains
of the outfit.

36:23.347 --> 36:24.482
As a matter of fact,
with everything we do,

36:24.515 --> 36:25.683
you're always right.

36:25.716 --> 36:27.318
And that means therefore,

36:27.351 --> 36:30.388
I am...

36:30.421 --> 36:31.689
always wrong.

36:31.722 --> 36:33.558
So I'm telling you
right up front, Teller.

36:33.591 --> 36:35.293
I'm gonna tell you
right to your face.

36:35.326 --> 36:37.195
This trick

36:37.228 --> 36:40.464
will go wrong.

36:40.498 --> 36:41.999
It really will.
It's gonna wrong.

36:42.033 --> 36:43.034
It's not gonna go well.

36:43.067 --> 36:47.538
But so perfectly

36:47.572 --> 36:49.473
wrong...

36:49.507 --> 36:52.043
that I might

36:52.076 --> 36:54.679
fool you.

36:54.712 --> 36:57.481
Now, you've got one card.
It's either black or red.

36:57.515 --> 36:59.483
There's no magic in that.

36:59.517 --> 37:02.353
And I am gonna take
and show you one card.

37:02.386 --> 37:05.122
Now, if you were doing this,
the card that I showed you

37:05.156 --> 37:08.025
would match the color
of the card you have.

37:08.059 --> 37:09.694
But I do everything wrong.

37:09.727 --> 37:12.597
So, when I pull this card out
and show it to you like this,

37:12.630 --> 37:14.532
and I see that
that's a black card,

37:14.565 --> 37:17.368
that means,
because I'm always wrong,

37:17.401 --> 37:19.503
that you picked a red card,
is that right?

37:19.537 --> 37:20.638
You picked a red card.

37:20.671 --> 37:22.607
So that is

37:22.640 --> 37:26.210
the wrong color.

37:26.244 --> 37:28.980
And this is

37:29.013 --> 37:32.450
the wrong suit.

37:32.483 --> 37:34.218
So I know
it's a heart or a diamond.

37:34.252 --> 37:37.388
Now, you would pull out
the suit that matched yours.

37:37.421 --> 37:39.023
But I don't do that.
I do everything wrong,

37:39.056 --> 37:40.224
so that's a heart,

37:40.258 --> 37:43.294
which means
you have picked a diamond.

37:43.327 --> 37:46.364
Now, to see if it's a face card
or a number card,

37:46.397 --> 37:47.498
I do this.

37:47.531 --> 37:49.634
And that shows me
that it is a number card

37:49.667 --> 37:50.968
'cause that's a face card,

37:51.002 --> 37:53.137
'cause I'm doing
everything wrong, Teller.

37:53.170 --> 37:56.674
Everything wrong.
[laughter]

37:56.707 --> 37:59.210
Now, this one tells me
if it's odd or even.

37:59.243 --> 38:00.478
And I see that that's even,

38:00.511 --> 38:02.413
so I know
that your card is odd.

38:02.446 --> 38:03.914
Is that correct?

38:03.948 --> 38:06.651
And I know it's not
any of these odd cards,

38:06.684 --> 38:08.753
ace, three, five, nine.

38:08.786 --> 38:10.921
So you have picked
the seven of diamonds.

38:10.955 --> 38:12.123
Is that correct?

38:12.156 --> 38:13.357
Picked the seven of diamonds.

38:13.391 --> 38:15.359
Pull out the seven of diamonds,

38:15.393 --> 38:18.095
and show it to the audience.

38:18.129 --> 38:19.764
Show it
to the audience triumphantly.

38:19.797 --> 38:21.766
The seven of diamonds.

38:21.799 --> 38:23.167
Now you're gonna go over there,
and you're gonna sit down,

38:23.200 --> 38:25.269
and you're gonna do this alone.

38:25.303 --> 38:28.372
It's just me versus you,
one-on-one.

38:28.406 --> 38:30.641
Mano a mano,
Penn versus Teller.

38:30.675 --> 38:33.544
But you need a mouthpiece.

38:33.577 --> 38:36.480
You need someone
to speak for you.

38:36.514 --> 38:39.216
So we are gonna have
a mutual friend of ours,

38:39.250 --> 38:42.520
Piff the Magic Dragon,
a friend to us all.

38:42.553 --> 38:46.857
Now Piff will sit in my seat,

38:46.891 --> 38:48.826
and Piff will do
the talking for you.

38:48.859 --> 38:49.827
Good luck.

38:49.860 --> 38:52.530
- Penn Jillette, everyone!

38:52.563 --> 38:54.832
[cheers and applause]

38:56.534 --> 38:59.403
Well, that was very impressive.
- Well, thank you, thank you.

38:59.437 --> 39:01.238
- How long
have you been doing magic?

39:01.272 --> 39:03.174
- Uh...
[laughter]

39:03.207 --> 39:06.644
I've been doing magic
for about 45 years.

39:06.677 --> 39:08.079
- Okay, all right.

39:08.112 --> 39:09.747
- Since I met Teller.
- So still relatively new.

39:09.780 --> 39:11.916
- Yeah.
[laughter]

39:11.949 --> 39:13.484
- This is such a surprise
for Teller.

39:13.517 --> 39:15.252
Did you see his face?
- Teller had no idea.

39:15.286 --> 39:16.754
- No clue.

39:16.787 --> 39:19.323
- Teller just thought
we were doing an extra fooler.

39:19.357 --> 39:21.125
- So, technically,
you've already fooled him.

39:21.158 --> 39:22.593
- If nothing else,

39:22.626 --> 39:23.961
I think we may not
have fooled him,

39:23.994 --> 39:25.596
but we certainly surprised him.

39:25.629 --> 39:27.331
- Definitely. I think if you
don't get the trophy,

39:27.365 --> 39:29.133
you at least deserve a plaque.

39:29.166 --> 39:30.701
- I deserve
some sort of plaque.

39:30.735 --> 39:32.670
- Right. Yeah.
Oh, are you ready already?

39:32.703 --> 39:34.038
- We are ready.
- [gasps]

39:34.071 --> 39:35.306
- Okay.
- I'm ready.

39:35.339 --> 39:37.341
- Here we go.
- Let's go to Piff and see

39:37.375 --> 39:40.778
if Teller knows
how you did your trick.

39:40.811 --> 39:43.514
- All right.

39:43.547 --> 39:47.518
Well, Teller has given it
his best shot,

39:47.551 --> 39:51.021
and he says that Penn has
completely fooled him, so...

39:51.055 --> 39:53.524
- Well, thank you so much.
Let's bring down the--

39:53.557 --> 39:55.326
[laughter]

39:55.359 --> 39:56.827
- I feel like
that's not what happened.

39:56.861 --> 39:58.996
- Is that not correct?

39:59.029 --> 40:00.064
I think
I might've misunderstood.

40:00.097 --> 40:01.232
Hang on a second.

40:01.265 --> 40:02.833
Can you just run that
by me one more time?

40:02.867 --> 40:05.669
Just whisper--
just one more time.

40:07.772 --> 40:10.975
He says, "Fool me once,
shame on you."

40:11.008 --> 40:12.476
[Alyson laughs]

40:12.510 --> 40:13.577
That's it,
just shame on you.

40:13.611 --> 40:15.579
[laughter]

40:15.613 --> 40:18.048
Teller also said to me
that Piff and Teller

40:18.082 --> 40:20.050
has a much stronger ring to it.

40:20.084 --> 40:22.386
[mutters]

40:22.420 --> 40:26.223
- But if nothing else, Teller,
I did surprise you, didn't I?

40:26.257 --> 40:28.225
- He says,
"No, he knew it all along."

40:28.259 --> 40:30.928
[laughter]

40:30.961 --> 40:32.563
- Piff, thank you so much.

40:32.596 --> 40:34.031
Thank you
for being in my corner,

40:34.064 --> 40:37.067
but I believe
that we have to do this

40:37.101 --> 40:39.069
very specially,
just one-on-one.

40:39.103 --> 40:41.071
Teller, come up here.
We'll have a little discussion

40:41.105 --> 40:42.840
right here
in front of everybody.

40:42.873 --> 40:45.242
Okay, what do you got?

40:49.747 --> 40:52.082
We never--Teller knew nothing
about this till we did this.

40:52.116 --> 40:53.584
It really was
a complete surprise.

40:53.617 --> 40:55.586
We pretended we were just
shooting a regular fooler,

40:55.619 --> 40:57.588
and there's
no precedent for this,

40:57.621 --> 41:01.659
and Teller thinks
that I half-fooled him

41:01.692 --> 41:04.462
and maybe
we bring down the trophy

41:04.495 --> 41:06.030
and split it in half.
What do you think?

41:06.063 --> 41:07.898
Can we bring down the trophy?
- Yeah!

41:07.932 --> 41:10.000
[cheers and applause]

41:10.034 --> 41:14.138
- You can hold that.

41:14.171 --> 41:16.373
And we share
that trophy together.

41:16.407 --> 41:17.842
- Aw.

41:17.875 --> 41:21.011
[cheers and applause continue]

41:21.045 --> 41:24.148
We all just witnessed
Penn versus Teller.

41:24.181 --> 41:25.649
Penn even found a way to earn

41:25.683 --> 41:28.219
a fooler trophy
on his own show.

41:28.252 --> 41:30.354
Come back next week
for the reunion

41:30.387 --> 41:31.755
of Penn and Teller

41:31.789 --> 41:33.757
and more amazing magic.

41:33.791 --> 41:34.992
We'll see you soon.

41:35.025 --> 41:37.561
[cheers and applause continue]
